The air inside the Thorn Estate tasted of old money and new fear. It was a specific flavor, Leo thought, as the heavy oak door shut behind him with a sound like a tomb sealing. Polished limestone underfoot, cold and echoing. The scent of beeswax and hothouse orchids, cloying and desperate. And beneath it, threading through the vast, over-decorated foyer, the faint, acrid tang of paranoia.

Julian Thorn awaited him in the grand salon, a room designed to intimidate. A thirty-foot ceiling vanished into shadow. A Titian glowered from one wall. Thorn himself was a spare man in an immaculate charcoal suit, perched on the edge of a Boulle chair as if it were a razor’s edge. His fingers, long and pale, drummed a silent, frantic rhythm on his knee.

“Vance.” The name was exhaled, not spoken. “You’re late.”

“Traffic,” Leo lied. The real delay had been a final, feverish cross-reference in his car, confirming his grim prediction: Thorn’s requested menu—a deceptively simple-sounding *Poulet au Miel et Lavande*—was, in its original 14th-century Provençal form, a ceremonial dish. It was served not with common honey, but with *miel fou*, “mad honey,” harvested from rhododendron flowers. In small doses, a euphoric; in the quantity a sauce would require, a neurotoxin causing paralysis, cardiac arrest.

The kitchen was a brutalist cathedral of stainless steel and black granite, a stark contrast to the antique opulence of the house. In its center, a stranger moved with quiet, lethal efficiency. He was tall, shrouded in a pristine white jacket, his face all sharp angles and deep hollows. His eyes, when they flicked up to meet Leo’s, were the color of dishwater. He didn’t speak. The only sounds were the hiss of a reducing stock and the precise *thock-thock-thock* of his knife on a board, mincing lavender.

“This is Chef Arto,” Thorn said, waving a dismissive hand. “He came highly recommended.”

Leo’s own knives, the familiar weight of them in their roll, felt like a useless anchor. He approached the central station. The ingredients were laid out with an almost surgical precision: the plump Bresse chicken, trussed; the bundle of Provençal lavender; a small, unlabeled jar of amber honey.

“May I?” Leo asked, reaching for the jar.

Arto’s hand shot out, covering his. The grip was cold, strong as a steel clamp. “The mise is set,” he said, his voice a low monotone. “Do not disturb.”

“Mr. Thorn,” Leo said, not breaking eye contact with the chef. “My terms for coming were explicit. I oversee. I taste. Every component.”

Thorn wrung his hands. “Is that necessary? The time—”

“It is the only reason I am here.” Leo put steel into his voice, the ghost of his old authority. “Or you can dine with your associate alone.”

A bead of sweat traced a path from Thorn’s temple to his jaw. He gave a tight, jerky nod.

Arto’s hand withdrew slowly. Leo unscrewed the jar. He dipped the tip of a small tasting spoon into the honey. He didn’t taste it yet. First, he smelled. The aroma was complex, floral, but with a faint, greenish undertone—a hint of damp earth and something vaguely medicinal. He touched a minuscule drop to the inside of his wrist, waited, felt a faint, unusual warmth. Finally, he brought the spoon to his lips.

The flavor bloomed: a burst of cloying sweetness, then a swift, aggressive bitterness that clawed at the back of his throat. A subtle numbness tingled on his tongue. His heart hammered against his ribs.

“This honey,” Leo said, his mouth dry. “Where did you source it?”

“A private apiary in the mountains,” Arto said, his gaze fixed on the chicken. “It is rare. Appropriate for the dish.”

“It’s toxic.” Leo turned to Thorn, whose face had gone the color of parchment. “Rhododendron honey. Even two tablespoons in the sauce would induce vomiting, dizziness, potentially fatal arrhythmias. This isn’t an ingredient. It’s a weapon.”

The silence that followed was absolute, broken only by the frantic drip of a tap. Thorn stared at the innocent-looking jar as if it were a coiled viper. His eyes darted to Arto, who had gone very still.

“You’re certain?” Thorn whispered.

“My palate,” Leo said flatly, “has never been wrong about poison.”

A strange sound escaped Arto—a sigh that was almost a hiss. He looked not at Thorn, but at Leo, and in those flat eyes, Leo saw a flash of something cold and appraising, the look of a master whose intricate work has been discovered by an unexpected connoisseur. Then, chaos.

With a sudden, violent sweep of his arm, Arto sent the heavy cast-iron skillet of hot stock flying across the range. It hit the controls. There was a spark, a *whump* of igniting gas, and a wall of flame roared up the stainless steel hood, greedily licking at the grease-caked filters.

“Fire!” Thorn shrieked, stumbling back.

Smoke, thick and black and smelling of burning fat and electronics, billowed forth, filling the kitchen with terrifying speed. The alarms screamed. Sprinklers erupted, a chaotic, drenching rain. In the strobe-like flash of the emergency lights and the orange dance of the flames, Leo lost sight of Arto. He lunged forward, not toward the exit, but toward the ingredient station, grabbing the toxic honey jar—evidence.

A shape barreled into him—Thorn, blind with panic, clawing his way to the door. They went down in a tangle of limbs on the wet floor. Leo’s head cracked against a cabinet handle. Stars exploded in his vision. By the time he shoved the sobbing mogul off him and staggered to his feet, the kitchen was a nightmare of steam, smoke, and cascading water. Arto was gone.

The fire, contained but vicious, was finally dying under the torrent from the sprinklers. The room was a wreck, dripping and scorched. Thorn, soaked and shaking, was being helped up by two wide-eyed security guards who had finally arrived.

“He tried to kill me!” Thorn jabbed a trembling finger at the spot where Arto had vanished.

Leo’s eyes scanned the room, searching for any sign of the chef. He spotted a small, almost imperceptible smudge of honey on the edge of the counter. He made a mental note to investigate further.

As the guards led Thorn away, Leo remained in the kitchen, surveying the damage. The air was thick with the acrid smell of smoke and the taste of fear. He knew that he had stumbled into something much larger than a simple poisoning plot. The game had just begun, and Leo was ready to play.

He took a deep breath, his mind racing with possibilities. He knew that he had to get to the bottom of this, to uncover the truth behind the poisoned honey and the sinister forces that had orchestrated this attack. He was a man on a mission, driven by a burning desire for justice and a need to uncover the truth.

